            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Gabriel Hayes\u2019s childhood in suburban Ohio was a world of straight lines and sensible expectations. His father, an engineer, and his mother, a high school math teacher, valued logic and stability, viewing Gabriel's constant sketching as a harmless but impractical hobby. This changed when his younger sister was diagnosed with a chronic illness. During long hospital stays, Gabriel saw how her guarded emotions found release in the vibrant, imaginary worlds she created with crayons and paper. It was a silent, powerful form of communication that left a permanent mark on him.\n\nInitially pursuing a \"safe\" degree in graphic design, Gabriel felt a profound sense of emptiness. He was creating for commerce, not connection. A late-night search led him to a graduate program in Art Therapy & Counseling Psychology. It was an immediate, resounding epiphany. He left the Midwest for San Francisco, a city that promised the creative freedom and progressive mindset he craved. The move was a personal and professional rebirth.\n\nNow 44, Gabriel has built a life of quiet purpose. For over a decade, he has worked as an art therapist, splitting his time between a public school and a community health clinic. He guides troubled adolescents and grieving adults, using clay, paint, and charcoal to help them articulate what words cannot. He is known for his calm, observant presence, a safe harbor in his clients' emotional storms.\n\nHe lives in NoPa with his partner of eight years, Marcus, a landscape architect. Their rent-controlled apartment is filled with plants and works-in-progress. Gabriel\u2019s daily routine is his anchor: a 3.5-mile bicycle commute through the Panhandle is his moving meditation, preparing him for the day and allowing him to decompress on the way home. San Francisco is more than a location; it's the backdrop to his chosen family and the city that allowed him to become himself. His dream is to one day open a small, sliding-scale art therapy studio in his own neighborhood, ensuring the healing power of creation he first witnessed in a stark hospital room is accessible to all."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was sixteen, the hospital air thick with antiseptic. His sister, made small by the bed, wasn\u2019t speaking that week. But her hand moved, pressing a yellow crayon into a defiant, blazing sun surrounded by scribbled darkness. In that silent creation, he saw not a drawing, but her voice\u2014a desperate, beautiful broadcast of her spirit. It was the moment he understood art\u2019s true purpose was not in perfection, but in translation. It became his life\u2019s foundational truth.\n\n2.\nIt was 2 AM in his bleak college apartment. On his screen was a sterile corporate logo he\u2019d been designing, a monument to emptiness. Then, on another tab, the words \u201cArt Therapy & Counseling Psychology.\u201d A jolt went through him, pure and electric, like a circuit finally connecting. In that instant, the grey world of his parents' expectations fractured, revealing a future of vibrant, messy, human purpose. It was a permission slip he wrote for himself, and he never looked back.\n\n3.\nHis first week in San Francisco, adrift and full of nervous hope. He stepped out of his new apartment into a cool evening fog that smelled of eucalyptus and damp earth. The ornate Victorian houses of NoPa, painted in defiant colors, seemed to lean in and welcome him. An overwhelming sense of relief washed over him. This wasn't just a new city; it was a different frequency, one his own soul was already tuned to. He felt he could finally exhale.\n\n4.\nYears into his practice, a teenage boy, silent with grief for weeks, sat before him. Gabriel simply slid a piece of charcoal across the table. The boy picked it up and drew a single, splintered glass, shards flying apart in violent stillness. Gabriel felt a familiar ache of recognition\u2014the same silent language his sister had spoken. In that shared, wordless understanding, his purpose was renewed. He wasn't fixing anyone; he was holding a safe space for the truth to appear.\n\n5.\nA Sunday morning, a few years ago. Sunlight streamed into their apartment, illuminating dust motes dancing around the fiddle-leaf figs Marcus so carefully tended. His partner was focused on a new orchid, his brow furrowed in concentration. Gabriel, sketchbook in lap, captured the quiet intensity of the moment. There was no great drama, just the profound, grounding peace of a shared life. It was the feeling of a chosen family, the steady joy that made his difficult work possible."
